We have a spring application as follows:

```
        SpringApplication app = new SpringApplication(Myeureka1Application.class);
                app.setRegisterShutdownHook(false);
                app.run(args);

```

We would expect that no shutdownhook will be registred, so that we can register an own extended shutDownHook. But instead the default shutDownHook will be registred.
The problem seems to result from the fact that there will be created one/more additional spring application/s and the original setting of registerShutDownHook will not be populated.

The reason why we want to register an own shutDownHook is that we want a micro service not to accept further requests but process the accepted requests until they are ready before the shutDown should complete.

Could you please avoid adding findMainClass dependency to each JavaExec task. Instead add it to spring-boot specific tasks only, like BootRunTask.
The reason is when I have my custom Gradle plugin which also uses spring-boot plugin, and where I have my own JavaExec task, e.g. for generating additional sources, I don't want my task to depend on spring-boot findMainClass, which would create circular dependency, because I want to hook my task as a dependency of compileJava task.

Instead of the code in RunPluginFeatures (around line 60) which looks like this:

```java
if (task instanceof JavaExec || task instanceof CreateStartScripts) {
    task.dependsOn(FIND_MAIN_CLASS_TASK_NAME);
}
```

I'd rather propose to change it to something like this:
```java
if (task instanceof BootRunTask || task instanceof CreateStartScripts) {
    task.dependsOn(FIND_MAIN_CLASS_TASK_NAME);
}
```

Thanks!

When Spring Boot starts an embedded Mongodb,
it extracts the mongod into a unique file every time it runs, for example:
C:\users\fmayer\appdata\local\temp\extract-b83962b6-16dc-4d2f-85ea-11e6c64d15c1mongod.exe

This is a problem with the Windows Firewall, because it means I have to approve a new executable to communicate through the Windows Firewall for every build.

this has been solved by flapdoodle:
https://github.com/sourcemuse/GradleMongoPlugin/issues/2

but it's impossible to choose the ip mongod should be bind to.


org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.mongo.embedded.EmbeddedMongoAutoConfiguration
```java	
@Bean
	@ConditionalOnMissingBean
	public IMongodConfig embeddedMongoConfiguration() throws IOException {
		IFeatureAwareVersion featureAwareVersion = new ToStringFriendlyFeatureAwareVersion(
				this.embeddedProperties.getVersion(),
				this.embeddedProperties.getFeatures());
		MongodConfigBuilder builder = new MongodConfigBuilder()
				.version(featureAwareVersion);
		if (getPort() > 0) {
			builder.net(new Net(getPort(), Network.localhostIsIPv6()));
		}
		return builder.build();
	}
```

should be
```java	
@Bean
	@ConditionalOnMissingBean
	public IMongodConfig embeddedMongoConfiguration() throws IOException {
		IFeatureAwareVersion featureAwareVersion = new ToStringFriendlyFeatureAwareVersion(
				this.embeddedProperties.getVersion(),
				this.embeddedProperties.getFeatures());
		MongodConfigBuilder builder = new MongodConfigBuilder()
				.version(featureAwareVersion);
		if (getPort() > 0) {
			builder.net(new Net("127.0.0.1",getPort(), Network.localhostIsIPv6()));
		}
		return builder.build();
	}
```
(or even better: use the host property `spring.data.mongodb.host=127.0.0.1`)
